  <title>Monte Carlo computation of \(L_p\) distance between two densities on the unit hypersphere</title>
  <dc:creator>Kisung You</dc:creator>
  <link>https://kisungyou.github.io/posts/note001-spherical-distance/index.html</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 




<section id="problem-statement" class="level1">
<h1>Problem Statement</h1>
<p>A <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?d">-dimensional unit hypersphere <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BS%7D%5Ed%20=%20%5Clbrace%20x%20%5Cin%20%5Cmathbb%7BR%7D%5E%7Bd+1%7D~%7C~%20%5C%7Cx%5C%7C_2%5E2%20=%20%5Csum_%7Bi=1%7D%5E%7Bd+1%7D%20x_i%5E2%20=%201%5Crbrace"> is one of the standard mathematical spaces in the field of <a href="https://doi.org/10.1201/9781351189675">objected-oriented data analysis</a> <span class="citation" data-cites="marron_2021_ObjectOrientedData">(Marron and Dryden 2021)</span>. Let <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathcal%7BP%7D(%5Cmathbb%7BS%7D%5Ed)"> denote a space of probability densities on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BS%7D%5Ed">. For two densities <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?f,g%5Cin%5Cmathcal%7BP%7D(%5Cmathbb%7BS%7D%5Ed)">, it is frequently needed to measure dissimilarity between the two. Unfortunately, even for the most well-known distributions on the hypersphere, analytic formula for any discrepancy measure is rarely available, leading to require numerical schemes for approximation. Here we focus on <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L_p"> distance between the two densities,</p>
<p><span id="eq-objective"><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0AL_p%20(f,g)%20=%20%5Cleft(%20%5Cint_%7B%5Cmathbb%7BS%7D%5Ed%7D%20%7Cf(x)%20-%20g(x)%7C%5Ep%20%5Cright)%5E%7B1/p%7D%0A%5Ctag%7B1%7D"></span></p>
<p>and we show how to combine Monte Carlo way of integration by means of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Importance_sampling">importance sampling</a> to approximate Equation&nbsp;1.</p>
</section>
<section id="computation" class="level1">
<h1>Computation</h1>
<p>Importance sampling requires a proposal density. The easiest choice is to use uniform density <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?u(x)"> as an importance proposal since sampling from <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?u(x)"> is trivial. First, take a random sample from standard normal distribution <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x%20%5Csim%20%5Cmathcal%7BN%7D(0,I)"> in <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathbb%7BR%7D%5E%7Bd+1%7D">. Then, the rest is to take <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?L_2"> normalization, i.e., <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x%20%5Cleftarrow%20x%20/%20%5C%7Cx%5C%7C_2">, which makes a sampled vector to have a unit norm. Given the sample generation process, we have the following</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cbegin%7Baligned%7D%0AL_p%20(f,g)%5Ep%20&amp;=%20%5Cint_%7B%5Cmathbb%7BS%7D%5Ed%7D%20%7Cf(x)-g(x)%7C%5Ep%20dx%20%5C%5C%0A&amp;=%20%5Cint_%7B%5Cmathbb%7BS%7D%5Ed%7D%20%5Cfrac%7B%7Cf(x)-g(x)%7C%5Ep%7D%7Bu(x)%7D%20u(x)%20%20dx%20%5C%5C%0A&amp;=%20%5Cmathbb%7BE%7D_%7Bu(x)%7D%20%5Cleft%5Clbrack%20%5Cfrac%7B%7Cf(x)-g(x)%7C%5Ep%7D%7Bu(x)%7D%20%5Cright%5Crbrack%5C%5C%0A&amp;%5Capprox%20%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7BN%7D%20%5Csum_%7Bn=1%7D%5EN%20%5Cfrac%7B%7Cf(x)-g(x)%7C%5Ep%7D%7Bu(x)%7D%20%5C,%5C,%5Ctextrm%7Bfor%7D%5C,%5C,%20x_n%20%5Coverset%7Biid%7D%7B%5Csim%7D%20u(x),%0A%5Cend%7Baligned%7D%0A"> where the last term gets better approximation as <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N%5Crightarrow%20%5Cinfty">.</p>
</section>
